# Purpose

Enforce backend layer boundaries, dependency direction, module structure, and the request context pattern.

# Rules

## Folder Structure

```
backend/src/
├── aop/          Cross-cutting concerns (db, exceptions, http, emitter, scheduler, logging, delegator)
├── config/       App configuration loaded from environment variables
├── lib/          Pure utility libraries (e.g. validation wrapper around Zod)
├── modules/      Feature modules: auth, jobs, docs
├── server/       Express server bootstrap and shutdown manager
├── services/     Stateless services (jwt, openapi)
├── shared/       Shared constants, enums, schemas, types used across modules
└── utils/        Pure utility functions (async, string, validation)
```

## Dependency Direction

`modules/` → `aop/`, `lib/`, `services/`, `shared/`, `config/`  
`aop/` → `lib/`, `shared/`, `config/`  
`modules/` MUST NOT import from other `modules/`.  
`config/` MUST NOT import application code.

## Module Structure

Each feature module (`auth`, `jobs`) MUST contain:

```
modules/<name>/
├── <name>-controller.ts   Request handlers — no business logic
├── <name>-middleware.ts   Input validation and route guards
├── <name>-routing.ts      Express Router wiring
├── <name>-registry.ts     OpenAPI path registration (zod-to-openapi)
├── schemas/               Zod schemas for request/response shapes
└── types/                 TypeScript types derived from schemas
```

## Context Pattern

Controllers access the database, scheduler, delegator, emitter, and user identity exclusively via `req.context`.  
DO NOT inject these as function parameters or module-level singletons inside controllers.

# Anti-Patterns

- DO NOT put business logic in controllers — throw typed exceptions from `aop/exceptions` instead.
- DO NOT import `aop/` from `modules/` bidirectionally.
- DO NOT import from other `modules/` within a module.
- DO NOT access `config/` from inside `modules/` through indirect re-exports that create circular paths.
